title: About
text:
Established at Michigan Medicine and based in the Department of Neurology, the Michigan Alzheimer’s Disease Center aims to:

Conduct and support research on Alzheimer’s disease and related dementias
Promote state-of-the-art care and wellness for individuals and families affected by memory loss
Increase dementia awareness through collaborative education and outreach efforts
Work to address racial and ethnic disparities in Alzheimer’s disease and related dementias
Provide training and support to the next generation of clinicians and scientists

title: About
text:
Meet the DMSC
The Data Management and Statistical Core (DMSC), led by Kelly Bakulski, PhD, helps maintain our center’s academic and research productivity by integrating and disseminating data to our research investigators. The data core manages data privacy, analyzes data for specific research projects, and facilitates data sharing nationally with the National Alzheimer’s Coordinating Center.

title: Allyson Gregoire
text:
Allyson Gregoire, Data Analyst/Programmer




Allyson joined the Michigan Alzheimer’s Disease Center in the summer of 2021 as a member of the data core team as a Data Analyst/Programmer. She earned her B.S. in Biochemistry and Molecular Biology from Michigan State University in 2016 and an MPH in Epidemiology from the University of Michigan in 2019. Allyson’s role in the data core includes working with center collaborators to perform statistical analyses and to support data management and dissemination. Allyson is a center resource for technical questions relating to R, Tableau, REDCap and SQL, and can serve as statistical analysis support for hypothesis testing and regression models including linear, logistic and Cox proportional hazards models. Allyson is currently working on expanding her expertise into -omics modeling and learning to be an at-home barista.
